HTML (HyperText Markup Language) entities are special codes used to display reserved characters or 
symbols that are not easily typed on a keyboard. These entities are often used to ensure that special 
characters are rendered correctly in web pages. Below are some common HTML entities and their uses:

Commonly Used HTML Entities
Reserved Characters

& (ampersand): &amp;
< (less than): &lt;
> (greater than): &gt;
" (double quote): &quot;
' (single quote): &apos; or &#39;
Non-breaking Space

(space): &nbsp;
Special Symbols

© (copyright): &copy;
® (registered trademark): &reg;
™ (trademark): &trade;
€ (euro): &euro;
£ (pound sterling): &pound;
¥ (yen): &yen;
Mathematical Symbols

± (plus-minus): &plusmn;
÷ (division): &divide;
× (multiplication): &times;
≤ (less than or equal to): &le;
≥ (greater than or equal to): &ge;
Greek Letters

α (alpha): &alpha;
β (beta): &beta;
γ (gamma): &gamma;
δ (delta): &delta;

Example Usage in HTML

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>HTML Entities Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <p>This is an ampersand: &amp;</p>
    <p>This is a less than sign: &lt;</p>
    <p>This is a greater than sign: &gt;</p>
    <p>This is a double quote: &quot;</p>
    <p>This is a single quote: &apos;</p>
    <p>This is a non-breaking space:&nbsp;in action.</p>
    <p>Special characters: &copy;, &reg;, &trade;, &euro;, &pound;, &yen;</p>
    <p>Mathematical symbols: &plusmn;, &divide;, &times;, &le;, &ge;</p>
    <p>Greek letters: &alpha;, &beta;, &gamma;, &delta;</p>
</body>
</html>